04288nam a22007095i 9789048505364DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20052005ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485053647 a10.1515/97890485053642doi  a(DE-B1597)532929  a(OCoLC)1110717014  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1998.3.L83bT49 2005eb 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/0233/0922221 aThompson, Kristin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHerr Lubitsch Goes to Hollywood :bGerman and American Film after World War I /cKristin Thompson. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b463 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One: Lubitsch's Career -- tChapter Two: Making the Light Come from the Story: Lighting -- tChapter Three: Subduing the Cluttered Background: Set Design -- tChapter Four: Guiding the Viewer's Attention: Editing -- tChapter Five: Peeking at the Players: Acting -- tChapter Six: Mutual Influences -- tEpilogue: The Lubitsch Touch -- tNotes -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aErnst Lubitsch, the German filmmaker who left Berlin for Hollywood in the 1920s, is best remembered today for the famous "Lubitsch touch" in such masterpieces as Ninotchka, which featured Greta Garbo's first-ever screen smile, and Heaven Can Wait. Kristin Thompson's study analyzes Lubitsch's earlier silent films of 1918 to 1927 in order to trace the mutual influences between the classical Hollywood film style as it had evolved in the 1910s and the German film industry of the same period, which had emerged from World War I second in strength only to Hollywood. During World War I, American firms supplied theaters around the world as French and Italian films had become scarce. Ironically, the war strengthened German filmmaking due to a ban on imports that lasted until 1921. During that period of isolation, Lubitsch became the finest proponent of German filmmaking and once Hollywood films appeared in Germany again Lubitsch was quick to absorb their stylistic traits as well. He soon became the unique master of both styles as the golden ages of the American and German cinema were beginning. This innovative study utilizes Lubitsch's silent films as a means to compare two great national cinemas at a vital formative period in cinema history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszUnited States. 0aMotion pictureszGermany. 0aMotion pictureszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048505364zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048505364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048505364.jpg  a978-3-11-070067-1  AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK